{"components":{"value":[{"value":{"data":{"value":{"text":{"value":"<p>We can now show that the sets <img src=\"https://s3.eu-west-2.amazonaws.com/scholar6/bricks/maths/CodeCogsEqn+(8).gif\" /> and <img src=\"https://s3.eu-west-2.amazonaws.com/scholar6/bricks/maths/CodeCogsEqn+(5).gif\" /> are the same size. It is easiest to illustrate a bijection with a diagram.</p> <img src=\"https://s3.eu-west-2.amazonaws.com/scholar6/bricks/maths/q5_diag1+(1).jpg\" style=\"margin:0 auto;width:100%;\" />  <p>Hopefully, you can see the pattern and figure out how it continues. Basically, every <i>odd</i> natural number <img src=\"https://s3.eu-west-2.amazonaws.com/scholar6/bricks/maths/CodeCogsEqn+(13).gif\" /> gets mapped to <img src=\"https://s3.eu-west-2.amazonaws.com/scholar6/bricks/maths/CodeCogsEqn+(12).gif\" /> and every <i>even</i> natural number <img src=\"https://s3.eu-west-2.amazonaws.com/scholar6/bricks/maths/CodeCogsEqn+(13).gif\" /> gets mapped to <img src=\"https://s3.eu-west-2.amazonaws.com/scholar6/bricks/maths/CodeCogsEqn+(14).gif\" />. This represents bijection: every element of <img src=\"https://s3.eu-west-2.amazonaws.com/scholar6/bricks/maths/CodeCogsEqn+(8).gif\" /> and every element of <img src=\"https://s3.eu-west-2.amazonaws.com/scholar6/bricks/maths/CodeCogsEqn+(5).gif\" /> has something mapped to it.</p>","type":"string"}},"type":"object"},"name":{"value":"Text","type":"string"}},"type":"object"},{"value":{"data":{"value":{"reveal":{"value":"7 is odd, so work out  <img src=\"https://s3.eu-west-2.amazonaws.com/scholar6/bricks/maths/CodeCogsEqn+(20).gif\" />","type":"string"},"text":{"value":"Which integer does the natural number 7 get mapped to?","type":"string"},"entries":{"value":[{"value":{"name":{"value":"","type":"string"},"answer":{"value":"3","type":"string"}},"type":"object"}],"type":"array"}},"type":"object"},"name":{"value":"ShortAnswer","type":"string"}},"type":"object"},{"value":{"data":{"value":{"text":{"value":"Which natural number gets mapped to the integer -10?","type":"string"},"entries":{"value":[{"value":{"answer":{"value":"20","type":"string"},"name":{"value":"","type":"string"}},"type":"object"}],"type":"array"},"reveal":{"value":"The number in question must be even.","type":"string"}},"type":"object"},"name":{"value":"ShortAnswer","type":"string"}},"type":"object"},{"value":{"data":{"value":{"text":{"value":"<p>So even though <img src=\"https://s3.eu-west-2.amazonaws.com/scholar6/bricks/maths/CodeCogsEqn+(5).gif\" /> seems bigger than <img src=\"https://s3.eu-west-2.amazonaws.com/scholar6/bricks/maths/CodeCogsEqn+(8).gif\" /> in some sense, it is in fact the same size. Remarkably, one can also construct a bijection between <img src=\"https://s3.eu-west-2.amazonaws.com/scholar6/bricks/maths/CodeCogsEqn+(8).gif\" /> and <img src=\"https://s3.eu-west-2.amazonaws.com/scholar6/bricks/maths/CodeCogsEqn+(9).gif\" />, so the set of rational numbers has the same cardinality as the set of natural numbers. All these infinite sets which have the same size as <img src=\"https://s3.eu-west-2.amazonaws.com/scholar6/bricks/maths/CodeCogsEqn+(8).gif\" /> are <i>countable</i> or <i>countably infinite</i>. The idea is that because they can be put into one-one correspondence with the natural numbers {1,2,3,...}, they can in some sense be counted, or listed.</p>","type":"string"}},"type":"object"},"name":{"value":"Text","type":"string"}},"type":"object"}],"type":"array"},"number":{"value":5,"type":"number"}}